segments.text: Charles Crawford, side two.
Not a doctor.
You're not a doctor?
I'm sorry.
You know, professors at A&M, you just assume that...
In those days, there were very few doctors on the campus.
Is that right?
There were not half a dozen when I first came on the faculty.
You didn't need your...
If a man had a master's degree, he was considered pretty well qualified.
I wish it were that way today.
You need your doctorate to...
It makes a difference.
We were talking about council meetings and
We were talking earlier about Lloyd Smith being the city manager.
He, as I understand it, he was called a business manager until 1944, and the council then implemented the city manager type of government.
Do you remember that?
I sure don't.
You don't?
Okay.
I have to admit I don't.
All right.
Do you remember how the operations of the city were financed?
How did you go about financing whatever projects?
Well, we had some city taxes, but they were very low, and we actually operated on a very small budget, just a shoestring, and the city manager, I don't imagine the city manager
got more than $300 a month.
And it was a full-time job.
Yes, it was a full-time job.
One time, another Mr. Brown, I can't think, he was a brother to Frank Brown, our main electrician for A&M, worked there in College Station in the city, worked
city office, I don't remember exactly what his position was, but I remember he worked, he was former partner of Brown Allen Old Mobile Cadillac Company, former partner in that business.
One of the councilmen?
No, he wasn't a councilman.
I don't remember what his position was.
He was employed in some way, but I kind of believe he might have been city manager.
One time.
Oh, he might have been.
Forgotten.
After all, a good many years have passed since those days.
That's right.
Well, did Lloyd Smith present the problems to the council?
I was wondering how, did he mainly take care of most of the problems?
He took care of most of them and he just consulted with the people on the council and whenever we'd have meetings, we'd discuss all the problems and see what
was going on and decide on things that needed to be done and he pretty well carried them out.
Do you think this was a good type of way to operate a city?
Well, I think at the time and under the circumstances why it wasn't bad.
In fact, there was so little money available that it was more or less, they cut
They operated just more or less on a very limited budget and carried on the business very informally.
I guess for those years it wasn't bad.
Wasn't bad.
No.
I think, okay, 1946, and this is towards the very end of your term, as I understood it from reading the minutes, the council decided to hold a bond election.
Do you remember that?
Because this is a big change.
They never had, you know, had never borrowed a great sum of money before.
Actually, I can't recall that.
You can't recall the bond?
No, I can't recall it.
Well, I might have the dates mixed up, so it may not have happened during your term.
Do you remember any kind of projects that the council wanted to do?
For instance, you were talking about paving the streets.
What other type of projects were you council interested in?
I don't actually remember any projects, just day-to-day operation and financing the operation by our taxes and they were very low and the amount of work being done was very, very limited.
So actually I don't remember any major projects except the street paving that was done by local forces
And it was, I don't believe we let any contracts outside of the city at that time.
Just went ahead and under the city manager, went up and had the streets graded, had the asphalt put down, and had the gravel put on top of that.
It was all done locally.
What streets were decided, how did you decide what streets would be paved this way?
I believe that the streets that were paved that way were those
The first that were south of the campus and they were only one or two, I guess there were three or four or five streets that were paved out for a half a mile from the campus.
And the same thing up in College Hills, East Gate.
There were several streets up there like Walton Drive and Main Drive up there.
several of those streets were black topped with local labor and with local supervision.
There was some point, and I'm not sure this is when you were council, that
the people that were on the street had to petition to have curb and gutters put in and the city would finance one-third and then the people would finance the other two-thirds.
Was that in your term?
I don't believe it was.
It was later on.
Yes, I believe it was.
We had very little curb in those days.
It was just basically this black topping as you were...
Yes, black topping.
The fire and the police department were real small.
The fire, you depended on A&M's fire department, and police maybe had one policeman?
I think I was about right.
About one policeman and just about all.
Was this adequate?
Well, for those days we had no particular trouble.
We had, as I recall, we never had any real disturbance in Bryan.
Occasionally somebody would have to be arrested, but it was very, very seldom.
And we had very little police work in those days.
And fire, were there not very many fires that you can remember?
I don't remember any major fires.
Maybe there was a few houses that were burned, but I really don't recall any major fires.
And the city used the A&M's fire department?
Yes.
Today, College Station places a lot of importance on having enough parks for the people.
Was this important when you were on the council?
We hadn't.
It was not important.
People had very little recreation area.

some areas that were left when the city was incorporated left vacant for parks, but as I recall, there's only a park of any considerable size or two, one down in the southwest of the campus and the other up in College Hills.
There's a little area in College Hills that's about Howard Judge
not more than three acres that's still in the parkway up there.
And there's a pipe swing up there that belonged to my daughter and it was moved off the campus when I moved from the campus up there.
And Frank Brown had pulled up from the ground and put it down out there in that park.
Is this where Thomas Park is today?
No, Thomas Park is in Bryan, isn't it?
No, well, I think Thomas Park is, if I'm correct, is the one that's right behind City Hall today.
Yes, I think that's... Is that where the park was?
Well, that was used mainly for storage for equipment in those days.
The area behind City Hall today?
What used...
Are you talking about the old City Hall down next to the railroad?
No, sir, the one that's presently at Eastgate, the one that's where we had the City Hall today, it's right across.
Well, this one is one up on Pereira.
Pereira, this old park that you're talking about?
Yes, that's the one I'm talking about.
Okay, I know where that is.
That's a couple blocks further back from the highway.
So the council really wasn't all that concerned with recreation.
No.
This is something that's developed later on.
Okay.
Zoning has always been important in College Station.
I don't think we had any zoning in those days.
Oh, you don't remember any zoning?
I don't remember any zoning.
But we do today.
Oh, yes.
Why do you think they implemented it?
Bryan doesn't have zoning, and College Station does.

Well, I think it was a desire of some people to see that there was an orderly development of the area, and they didn't want the areas to be so cluttered with some residences and some better sizes, but there was very little zoning going on at that time.
But later on they just wanted to make sure that they had... That's right.
Orderly development was needed.
And I think it's still needed.

Do you think it's not having zoning has hurt the way Bryan has developed as far as... Well, you see it's become such a city that since Bryan was not zoned, why, there were little patches of business, a business house or two here and there, little areas covered
not more than one or two blocks.
And it has not meant a very orderly development of the city because some of the people object to having a business next door.
And for that reason, why College Station, of course, has grown so rapidly in the last 15 years that if
I think it was highly desirable that certain areas be restricted to certain purposes.
Do you know why Bryan never zoned?
Since it grew up so slowly and it developed.
You see up until, compared with recent years, Bryan wasn't a very big town.
I can remember Bryan when it was only 10,000 people.
Oh really?
And when we moved to Bryan, I bet there weren't more than 8,000 to 10,000 people in Bryan.
And when was that?
When I moved to Bryan?
And it had been, I believe it has been a city or a settlement since like the 1840s.
Somewhere around that.
So it's an old city.
And Harvey Mitchell, the man who had a lot of influence in helping establish A&M,
was one of the merchants.
The story is told that a stranger rode up out to Boonville, which is about three miles east of Brown, out towards the road that leads over to Rams County and Highway 105.
Now, not 105 either.
Forgotten the number.
But anyway, there was a store there that had general merchandise.
and there was a man sitting on the store gallery.
You know what a gallery is?
No.
We call it a porch.
The porch.
Little porch or gallery.
There was a man sitting there, and this stranger rode up on a horse and says, this man greeted him and says, get down, stranger.
So he got down, came up, and he says, who is the...
I guess he was mayor.
He says, Harv Mitchell.
He says, well, courthouse right across there.
Is that the courthouse?
He said, yes.
He says, who's county judge?
He says, Harv Mitchell.
He asked several others, talked a little bit longer.
He says, I want to get the county clerk to record something.
He says, who is county clerk?
He says, Harv Mitchell.
Finally the man looked at him and says, is Harvey Mitchell the whole damn town?
He said, no, not at all.
He said, I'm Harvey Mitchell.
Oh, how funny.
That story, of course, I don't know whether it's true or not, but that's one I've heard many, many years ago.
Was this, if I've got this straight, he was in Boonville, at a store in Boonville?
Boonville, yeah.
Harvey Mitchell was sitting there?
Okay, okay.
You know that the building right next to the YMCA is Boyle Health Center.
Uh-huh.
That occupies the site that Harvey Mitchell Hall used to be on.
Oh, really?
That was a three-story building.
I believe it was a four-story building.
Anyway, it was the site of...
Harvey Mitchell Hall, named after Harvey Mitchell.
The pictures of the old buildings that are in your book, they're very beautiful buildings.
I'm sorry they don't exist today.
I know.
We've talked a little bit about this, but as I read the papers, there's a rather historic rivalry between Bryan and College Station.
After the organization of the College Station as a city, there was a good deal of rivalry.
There was a great deal of rivalry?
And some of the people felt very strongly about it.
There were a couple of men in Bryan who felt strongly about it, and then that engendered an anti-feeling out here.
So it was some pretty
pretty strong rivalry and pretty sharp words passed between some of the people between Bryan and College Station and yeah, Bryan and College Station.
Did the councils try to maintain peaceful relations?
We always had good relations with people in Bryan.
I know of no time when I was on the council had anything to do with it.
There was ever any real friction.
Do you remember
Mayor Langford had a brother, Ivan, and he was the mayor of Bryan, I believe.
He was mayor of Bryan for several terms and was later president of the Bryan Building and Loan.
He was.
He was in that new building when it was built at the present location of Bryan Building and Loan, which is now called Brazos Building and Loan.
Right, I've seen that.
Which has now been bought by the city savings and loan of
San Angelo.
Oh, really?
I didn't know that.
Same one that bought the community savings loan out here.
Oh, they bought that, too?
Yes, they just bought it.
I didn't know they had.
Those of us who own stock in it turned in our stock certificates within the last few days.
Because San Angelo bought the community savings bank that is on University?
Yeah.
It was bought by San Angelo?
That's right.
It was bought by City Savings Loan of San Angelo.
which is owned by the Lamar Savings Loan of Austin.
Are they going to still call it Community Savings Loan?
I don't know whether they'll continue to call it that or not.
Well, you turned in your stock certificate.
Did they pay you for it?
Well, they will.
They will.
Haven't yet.
We were talking about the rivalry between Bryan.
Do you know of any examples, anything that you can point to that might illustrate it, I guess?
I know that Mayor Jaeger was quite active in trying to incorporate College Station into Bryan.
And I don't know of any, yes I do, there was a lawyer by the name of Loth Henderson who was quite active in wanting to incorporate College Station into Bryan.
And I think they were two of the men that really did their best to prevent College Station being organized as a city.
I know that when Mr. Gilchrist was here as president, why, he and some of the men of Brown
who acted at that time would pace each other and wouldn't speak.
Oh, really?
Do you remember them going to the, I guess it might have been Attorney General, Brian, these Brian men, and trying to keep them from being College Station Incorporated?
No, I don't remember that.
Okay.
Did the council have any specific plan for growth?
No, no particular plan.
It really wasn't growing that fast?
No, it was growing steadily but not rapidly.
Like today, for instance.
Of course, the comparison between then and today is a contrast rather than a comparison because College Station and Bryan have become cities now.
And in those days, they were just country towns.
They were just country towns, even Brian was.
Do you remember any big problem during your term?
Any big problem that the council had to deal with?
Really, I don't.
I don't even recall any major problems that came up.
Of course, I'm sure there were some, but I wasn't involved, so I don't recall.
Do you feel like there was anything that you can name as a great achievement or one of the biggest achievements that the city and the council took care of when you were on the council?
I sure couldn't say that there was anything.
It was a great achievement because we were going along very
shall I say sedately and quietly and developing as new homes were built in the area.
And after it was unincorporated, of course, the area began to build up.
And that's the time when the Eastgate area developed several stores.
And the bus used to stop over at the Eastgate
But then came on into the campus and had a little stop on the corner of where next to the telephone office and had the bus stop right along there.
But in those days, it was just a very quiet little town going along about its business.
A&M was, at that time, only about 3,000 or 3,500 students.
See, when I entered A&M, there were only 1,100 students in all.
And half of those, nearly 600 of them, were freshmen.
Oh, my heavens.
Half of them were freshmen.
And you see, that meant that the buildings on the campus
take care of things pretty well.
And academic building was always one of the major class buildings, classroom buildings.
And that's where the president's office was for many years.
You see, the old main building burned in 1912.
And they think it was an arson.
Oh, they did?
A bunch of students.
Oh, how terrible.
It destroyed the building there.
They tried to
tried to knock down the walls of that building after the fire, and they got some of the artillery cannons from A&M and got out there and tried to shoot those walls down, and they couldn't budge them.
Those cannonballs would go into those walls.
They were about two feet thick, two and a half feet thick, but it was a loss of a real good building there, and it was a real setback for A&M.
They don't make buildings like that today, do they?
No, they don't.
I'll tell you, the present academic building is built almost that way.
It's very thick walls.
It looks that way.
And Dr. F.E.
Gieske was the architect on that building.
He was one of the first two A&M graduates to get a degree in A&M.
Oh, and become an architect.
Later on, he was...
head of the architecture department, head of the drawing department, then also head of architecture and architectural engineering.
You said that there was some stores that built at Eastgate.
What were these stores that built at Eastgate?
Luke's Grocery was the only one that I remember.
I believe that there was a real estate office, Color Pepper Real Estate, if I'm not mistaken.
But Luke's Grocery was the
main one and that's where people in that area over there across the road, highway, traded mostly.
What were the citizens of College Station like?
What was the character of the town?
Mainly good old country folks.
Very friendly?
Yes, very friendly.
Since you have your south and your east and your north, do you feel like that divided the city?
Was the city unified?
It didn't unify, but it didn't seem to separate.
In other words, it was a matter of convenience.
It wasn't a matter of rivalry so much.
It was a matter of convenience for the people who lived close to the campus.
North Gate has been there the longest, then the South Gate, and then East Gate.
And as the area developed, residential area, why, the people in that area, a lot of them didn't have automobiles.
Automobiles were not as numerous in that day as they are now.
But it was no particular rivalry.
It's just a matter of convenience.
From having stores there?
Yeah, having stores where they can shop.
Did College Station have any kind of transportation for its citizens?
No.
At one time there was a bus that ran out from Bryan to College Station.
I don't know how to call it.
Bryan, after the trolley was discontinued, there was a bus service.
And lots of people rode the bus for a good many years from Bryan out to College Station.
But as far as getting around College Station, there really wasn't... No, there was nothing.
No bus service within the city itself.
It's between Bryan and College Station.
Can you describe the leadership of Ernest Langford?
He ran the city for 20 years, and unfortunately he died a couple years ago.
So...
Ernest Langford was a very unusual individual and he came to A&M in the drawing department after he'd been out of school, out of A&M, only about two or three years.
He went over to Austin and was in architectural drafting as a draftsman, as an architect over there for about
I think it was about three years, and that's where he married.

And he and Ms. Langford were married in Austin and came to College Station, and he taught for several years until Dean Nagel, he had an opportunity for a scholarship up at the University of Illinois, and he went in to see Dean Nagel about it,
Dean Nagel was the first dean of engineering at A&M in 1911 or 12.
And when he told Mr. Nagel about it, why, Mr. Nagel says, I want you to take it.
He said, I'll write out your resignation right now.
He said, I'll take care of that.
So he just practically pushed him out the door.
And he went to University of Illinois.
And he was at University of Illinois about,
I don't know, six or seven years where he got his master's degree and also designed one of the houses that won a national award for a two-story home.
And then after Dean Bolton became dean, he got Mr. Lankford to come back in the architecture department because
There'd been several architects in the meantime, and he got Mr. Langford back.
And Mr. Langford was head of the architecture department from, I'm not sure of the years, but I would say for at least 20 years.
He was made head of architecture, I believe, the same summer that I was made head of mechanical engineering.
I'm not positive of that, but I think that's right.
at that time.
And then when he was elected mayor, he spent many, many hours down at the office there and devoted a great deal of time to the city.
And he did, I guess he made as big a contribution to the city of College Station as any one man ever did.
And he

was also when he retired he was made archivist and at that time we had no archival department and he became archivist and was given one room over in the MSC as his and he began to collect things he was the second archivist Mr. Cofer was the first and Mr. Cofer retired professor of English and
He served as archivist for, I'd say, two or three or four years.
And then Mr. Lankford came in.
And he occupied that office until the new Cushing Library was built.
And they gave him a room in the Cushing Library.
And he was archivist there for a good many years.
He read extensively.
He was a very voracious reader and also wrote a number of pamphlets and things that had to do with the development of A&M University, Texas A&M.
But he had one son, Keith, and Keith, after he moved off the campus and built his home,
down on Langford Street, where he and Leela lived there until Mr. Langford died.
Mr. Langford died at about 91 years old.
Oh, I know.
Yeah, something like that.
But Ms. Langford still lives down there, and I talk to her occasionally.
Do you know what subdivision that is in?
No, I don't.
It's on Langford Drive.
Yeah.
Named for him.
That's right.
Well, as a mayor, did he show a lot of foresight?
Did he want to plan?
Yes, he did quite a bit of planning, and he had a lot to do with the development and layout of the streets and things at College Station, especially that south Texas area.
Also, he was instrumental in working in that northeast area up there where I lived.
But he made a good mayor and devoted a lot of time to it, and especially in setting taxes and tax hearings, things like that.
He was quite active in things like that.
Well, he sounds like a remarkable man.
He was a remarkable individual.
Did you have any time on the council that some of the council members had different opinions?
There was only one time.
while I was on the council in those four years, that we had a real disagreement and difference of opinion and had a split vote.
And that split vote was about five to one.
What was it over?
Over giving special electric rates to the First Baptist Church.
And what was the outcome?
Well, I don't remember exactly what it was, but they worked out a program that was mutually agreeable between Brother Brown and the rest of the council.
Oh, I see.
I see.
He wanted electric rates.
That was the only time that we ever had a real split in the vote.
Was Mr. Langford able to?
He was pretty politic in there.
I only saw him lose his temper one time during the whole time that I worked with him, and that was with Mr. Clark, who developed that southwest area.
But he and Mr. Clark had a difference of opinion.
He kind of lost his temper one time.
Do you remember what that was all about?
It was about some tax renditions in areas where Professor Clark was developing new...
The Knoll?
Yeah, Knoll.
And Dr. Clark didn't agree with the tax assessment?
Well, we didn't agree with Dr. Clark.
He wanted certain tax concessions and
renditions much lower than we felt was reasonable.
And we just disagreed with him and put him down.
And so the council set the rate and he had to pay it?
Well, it was just a matter of, you know, they have what they call an equalization board.
And they get together every year, or I guess it is every year, maybe every other year, and go over the renditions and see if

taxes have been rendered somewhat equally and equal values equal equal projects and I've served on that two or three different times and we always tried to look at the situation find out other where other houses were valued just about the same that were equal value cost and
It was just a matter of routine operation.
Of course, we had tried to keep the tax values down and keep them at least equalized.
That was the whole point of it.
And the assessment that the board made, Dr. Clark, was in agreement?
Well, the assessments were made by the city, by the council and the city.
I don't remember who was on the tax board, but the
I can't think of the name of that group, the Equalization Board.
We would be appointed from year to year in different groups, and they would try their best to satisfy the people and to see that things were fair.
Did most people pay their taxes?
Oh, yes.
Very little trouble with people not paying taxes.
So the character of the town was a...
Oh yeah.
Very caring type of town.
Most people cooperating with, most people in College Station were pretty proud of this city.
They were pleased with it.
They had reason to.
And you see when they, you kept the same mayor for nearly 20 years, well you know that things were running along pretty smoothly.
That's right.
Wasn't much division.
That's right.
Very good point.
As I was reading your book, I noticed that many of the professors in the engineering department or people who were connected with the engineering department also became involved with the city.
There's all sorts of men.
Is there any particular reason?
Well, they were just interested and felt like they could render a service.
Now, Joe Orr was a professor of civil engineering, and there's a street down there named Orr Street.
It was a matter of interest and a matter of feeling that they could do a job that was worthwhile.
Can you tell me anything about Mr. Orr?
He also, his dad, he seemed to also be a leader in the community.
Joe was pretty forthright in his speaking and his approach to things.
And if he disagreed, why, he said so.
He spoke up and expressed himself.
But as a civil engineer, he was interested in, of course, the streets and the paving, and did have quite a bit of influence in some of the major engineering problems in the city.
So, Joe was, had been in South America
after he graduated from A&M and came back to A&M and was mainly surveying.
And he was one of the few, at that time, one of the few licensed land surveyors in the area.
And he trained lots of students in the area of plain surveying.
He surveyed the boundaries of College Station.
I think he also surveyed this spot right here.
Oh, really?
For Bryant?
Yeah.
Well, he did it for me.
I wanted to have my corners specified and have them certified, so I got a licensed surveyor to do that after I bought the lot.
But do you feel like College Station was lucky to have men such as?
Yes, I do.
I think those men served well and did a good job.
I think it was a very unselfish service.
and you didn't receive any money.
No, no money.
But is there an advantage in having people from a university running the city?
Well, it's changed now.
So the city and the university both have completely changed.
They're not the same place they were 30 years ago.
And at that time, the majority of people
at the college station were employed by A&M.
Today, that isn't the case.
That's true.
The same way with Brian.
You see, at present time, the faculty of A&M forms, say, 2,500 people.
I don't know what it is, but out of 50,000.
So that's a very small percentage.
In those days, it was a much larger percentage.
Almost all of the people.
That's right.
That's interesting.
Let me see.
How do you feel about the way College Station has developed?
There's a push to bring more industry in this area.
Do you feel like that is needed here?
Or why didn't you want it when you were coming down?
Since it's become a city.
why it's pretty necessary that they have some industry.
And I'm not too happy with large quantity of industry, but it's necessary to develop a city to have a tax base that can do things.
And if you don't have some industry, all the burden has to be borne by ad valorem tax on property.
And if you want to expand and really have some activity, why, you need the industry.
Now then, I've been surprised at the amount of heavy industry in North Brown.
I know.
There's a lot.
There's much more industry there than I had any idea would ever develop in Brown.
Now, College Station is trying to get some medium industries.
Also, something in the way of advanced technology.
To go along with the college?
And this Texas Instruments out here is located right across the East Bypass.
And since it is a highly scientific group, it can tie in with the instruction.
And it's a good contact.
for students and for the university.
And with several of those, that type of industry, why, it would become a real asset to our teaching.
So it is, now, in some ways, it doesn't improve the residential area, but if it's properly segregated and properly zoned, why, it still doesn't,
those industries are pretty good neighbors.
And they quite often do things that are needed, and they also separate their areas from the residential area in a way that isn't very objectionable.
When you were on the council, however,
We didn't have problems like that.
You didn't need to worry about bringing in industry?
You didn't feel like it was, town was ready for it?
We weren't concerned with it.
How would you have liked to see College Station develop differently, or would you have?
Well, to tell you the truth, I've
don't know the answer to that question.
I don't know how it would have been very different.

And since it grew up gradually and changed over a long period of time, and I was here all that time, the changes were so gradual that I wasn't too aware of just how it was going, especially in recent years.
See, I've been retired nearly 18 years.
And since that time, boy, there's lots of development been going on.
So I really wasn't too involved in it.
Is there anything else that you would like to add that I haven't asked about?
Any bit of information that would be interesting to people about College Station?
Well, of course, you're interested in the city of College Station more than you are in Texas A&M, aren't you?
Well, yes, sir, but I know they're tied together.
There have been certain people that have contributed to A&M that I think stand out.
For instance, Dean Nagel, first dean of engineering.
And he was head of the civil engineering department.
And then you see one time civil engineering and physics were combined.
Of course, most people don't know that.
He was dean of engineering for several years and then he became Texas' first water engineer.
And he went to Austin and was gone for a few years and during that time Dean Spence was dean, but Dean Spence died after a few years and they got Dean Nagel back here.
And Dr. Brazell was, I think, one of the outstanding presidents that A&M has ever had.
And then Dean Nagler resigned a second time, and that's when Dean Bolton became Dean of Engineering.
And Dean Bolton had a lot to do with A&M.
He was a very quiet individual, but very thorough, and he
was known as Bad Tracks.
That was his nickname, head of the electrical engineering department.
He first started as professor.
